Containers, the other compute model.

A container packages your application, its runtime, and its dependencies into a single image that runs identically wherever a container engine exists. Containers boot in seconds, share the host kernel rather than virtualizing hardware, and are the unit of deployment for almost every modern microservice.

The container model fits exactly where Lambda doesn't: long-running processes beyond Lambda's fifteen-minute cap, sustained see-pee-you or memory where per-invocation pricing loses to per-hour, workloads that need finer control over the runtime than Lambda exposes, and existing apps that are already containerized.

AWS runs containers three ways: the elastic container service for native orchestration, the elastic Kubernetes service for managed Kubernetes, and Fargate as the serverless compute engine underneath either of them.
